COVID is the Third or Fourth Cause of Death in Most Age Groups

Nathan (Nat) Goodman

October 31, 2021

TBD Counts of cases, hospital admissions, and deaths are key metrics of COVID-19 prevalence and burden, and are the basis for model-based estimates and predictions of these statistics. I present here graphs showing these metrics over time in Washington state and a few other USA locations of interest to me. I update the graphs and this write-up weekly. Previous versions are here. See below for caveats and technical details.

The gruesome body count of COVID deaths is mind-numbing. Sadly reminiscent of the body counts from the Vietname for those old enough to remember.

In this blog post, I try to put the death toll in context by comparing annual COVID deaths to the leading causes of non-COVID deaths. In the USA as a whole COVID kills almost as many people as cancer and far more than accidents. In Washington State, looking at all ages, COVID kills more people than Alzheimers disease; among the elderly (people 80 years and above), COVID kills more than stroke or lung disease; among young adults (20-24 years old), COVID kills almost as many as cancer and more than homicide or heart disease.

Figures 1a-b show COVID deaths in the USA and Wshington State. The first graph is the familiar cumulative death count per capita over time. The second graph annualizes the numbers so we can compare COVID deaths to other leading causes of death (usually expressed annually). The cumulative graph increases. The annualized graph fluctuates up and down reflecting the several COVID waves weve experienced.

The next two graphs (Figures 2a-b) show the same kind of data for Washington State broken down by age.
